## ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Real World Example

Soch **tumhare ghar me ek room hai**, aur us room ke andar **2 laptops** rakhe gaye hain.

* Tumne ek **private switch (router nahi)** lagaya hai jo sirf room ke laptops ko connect karta hai.
* Ab dono laptops ek dusre se **file share, games, chat** sab kar sakte hain âœ….
* Lekin wo **bahar ke world (Internet ya ghar ke aur devices)** se connect nahi kar sakte âŒ.

ğŸ‘‰ Matlab **room = VirtualBox Internal Network**
ğŸ‘‰ Aur **laptops = tumhari Virtual Machines**

---

## ğŸ”¹ Step 2: VirtualBox me kaise hota hai

Jab tum VirtualBox me **Adapter ko Internal Network select karte ho**, tum ek **network name** dete ho (e.g., `intnet`).

* Jo bhi VM tum is `intnet` network me add karoge â†’ **wo ek dusre ko dekh sakti hain**.
* Lekin **host machine** (tumhara asli laptop) ya **internet** unhe nahi dikhta.

---

## ğŸ”¹ Step 3: Example with IPs

Maan lo tumhare paas do VM hain:

* VM1 (Ubuntu): IP â†’ `192.168.10.2`
* VM2 (Windows): IP â†’ `192.168.10.3`
  Dono ka adapter = Internal Network `"intnet"`.

ğŸ‘‰ Agar VM1 se tum `ping 192.168.10.3` karoge â†’ **Reply milega âœ…**
ğŸ‘‰ Agar VM1 se tum `ping google.com` karoge â†’ **Reply nahi milega âŒ**
ğŸ‘‰ Agar VM1 se tum Host machine ko ping karoge â†’ **Reply nahi milega âŒ**

